reviews_data.review_text: My friend and I visited the Concord Mac Tabby Cat Cafe for the first time last night.  It is a great older repurposed building that is tastefully decorated and spotless.  The staff was extremely friendly and helpful.  We each enjoyed a local beer and one hour in the cat room.  There were a few other folks in the cat room with us and several others in other parts of the venue enjoying their beverages and the trendy atmosphere.  It was well worth the 45 minute drive from Mooresville for us two cat people and we will go back.  Unless, of course, they decide to open up another location up our way . . . that would be awesome!  If you are not necessarily a cat person but live nearby and are looking for an interesting coffee shop . . . this is your place.
I love cats and the coffee was amazing would definitely come back!!! 🤍🤍🤍🤍
Incredibly helpful and extremely pleasant staff! Coffee was awesome and who doesn't love petting cats! Will definitely return and highly recommend.

you are unable to pick up the cats, however they are very friendly and will come up to you. it’s clear that these kitties are well-cared for and that their needs are met. they are able to leave whenever they wish- but there are always multiple cats hanging around the humans in my experience.

reviews_data.review_text: Finally had a weekend to take my 7 year old to a cat cafe without her brother and dad who are allergic to cats. I called this place in advance to ask if we needed a reservation after being turned away from the Rock Hill cat cafe because they were booked. I’ve never been to one before I didn’t know you had to make a reservation and then when I finally did, drove 40 mins to get there, never in my life been to NoDa (I’m from out of state), paid for parking only for them to say they didn’t have any room either. No accommodation no sympathy, just pure laziness. I even explained the situation and disappointment from Rick hill but there was absolutely no customer service or hospitality. Ruined a 7 year olds weekend who waited several months to go to a cat cafe.
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Hello Natalie!
As our team let you know on the phone, we do hold spaces for walk in guests on a first come, first served basis for those without a reservation. You came in around 1:30 and the closest we could get you in to see the cats was around 3:30. We offered those spots to you. You declined. We then offered to bring a cat to the door for your daughter to pet to try to make her happy but you left. We did try to offer you what we could, given the current circumstances of your visiting hour. We care about our customer service and we all try to go above and beyond for our guests. 
There is not laziness on our team. We do the best we can in any situation, however there are rules and circumstances to also adhere by. We understand that people are disappointed when they can't go in to see the cats when they would like, however, we can only allow 12 people in the cat room at a time. We encourage reservations on our website, Instagram and Facebook. Our website has all info about how to get a reservation, when is the best time to visit with kids, where to park, how it works and what to expect. We try to educate anyone coming in advance so guests aren't upset for any reason when arriving. We know that for many, it is a first time cat cafe experience! We are open 7 days per week, reservations can be made online which will guarantee your spot when you arrive... we would love for you to bring your daughter back for an experience with us! We know you will enjoy it! That said, everyone is entitled to an opinion so we are not discounting your personal experience if that is how you felt while visiting that day, but we stand by our team and the love they all have for the guests walking in the door. Our team was giving you the options they had within the rules and guidelines as to how we operate. This was nothing personal and we would never want anyone to leave upset, which is why we keep as much information online and in all places where the Mac Tabby info is available. We hope you'll give us another shot!

The building is a beautiful old 1886 building that is sadly smushed in between two modern soulless seven-story apartment boxes.  Inside there's a small coffee shop area and the separate cat room. reviews_data.review_text:
Hello all! If there has ever been a hard review for me to write, it is this one. I have been debating it for days, but I decided it’s a big enough issue that I should follow through with it. I’d like to preface by saying that me and my boyfriend have come to the Charlotte Mac Tabby location for 3+ years. We have been loyal customers. It’s a date we always look forward to and count the days down on!

Last Wednesday I had a laparoscopic ovarian cystectomy with the addition of a surprise laparoscopic uterosacral nerve ablation. I decided to book a one-hour kitty date for me and my boyfriend, who goes to college in Virginia and came to visit me during this difficult time of my life, for that Saturday to get me out of the house. Oh boy! I woke up that morning feeling the worst I had since the surgery, it was rough but I decided the date would be worth it. Or so I thought.

For those used to the Charlotte location, you know there is a troublesome flight of stairs leading up to the door. About 20-30. I had told my boyfriend to stay behind me in case I fall or become weak, as this was the first time I had been out of the house since surgery as well as the first flight of stairs I walked up. For some reason, a worker of Mac Tabby (white, middle-aged+, average height male) who was sweeping the area above the stairs decided it would be the perfect time to make side comments about how “it must be such a workout going up those stairs” for me. We did not respond at first, as I was more concerned with not tripping over my own feet, however; he did not let this stop him. He continued making the same comment 2 or 3 more times about the stairs being “such a workout” for me. Once I got to the top of the stairs I informed him I had surgery, but rather than apologize he doubled down and said once more how rough it must be to walk up some stairs with a sarcastic tone. Wow, how kind.

I tried to not let it bother me at first, although later I lost that battle and brought it up to a worker who seemed to understand where I was coming from and decided to get the owner involved. Once the owner came over she did not seem as understanding. At all. Right off the bat, how I felt was dismissed by her and she made excuses for him saying they say that to each other all the time and there’s no way he could’ve known I had surgery. That’s the point! You are coworkers, you know each other. He does NOT KNOW ME! Or what I’ve been through!! I am highly disappointed that it took me showing this lady my stitches and bruises for her to act as if she knew where I was coming from. Bottom line, don’t make comments about your customers you do with your coworkers. Do not make comments with them, especially ones that can be taken as very rude and demeaning. You do not know what people struggle with every day. Some people have disabilities, and climbing those stairs may be the hardest part of their day- don’t be a jackass about it! Don’t make it harder! I don’t care if you make comments to each other at work, be careful who you say that shit to because I am not your coworker I am a paying customer who crawled out of her bed after a very rough surgery to try to have a better day. This experience demonstrates a lack of management understanding. Which is upsetting since me and my boyfriend really loved the experience this place brought us.

Needless to say, me and my boyfriend will not be back to this location. We will try our luck at other locations and pray we don’t have workers make comments about our body there. This has been a disappointing experience, to say the least.

Their drinks are pretty good though and the cats are innocent in all this. Adopt them!!

reviews_data.review_text: My  partner adopted a kitten from this place and the kitten essentially came to his home with a cold (Chex Mix). My partner was told that any watering eyes or sneezing is normal for kittens as they adjust, but within days this developed into a cold. His kitten now has red watery eyes and tons of sneezes.Usually, this is not a problem as most organizations will offer a low cost visit at an affiliated clinic and help the kitten they just adopted. However, after paying $140 for an adoption fee, which is steep and more than I’ve ever paid for my healthy humane society cats, they essentially told him to go find his own vet after a WEEK from his adoption date. Like I said before, the baby’s eyes were watery the DAY AFTER he got the kitten and they did not take the situation seriously. Just be warned that this organization facilitates over priced adoptions under the guise that the cats have been vetted but really they have been given shots, months prior, and they have no idea on the kittens current condition! Save yourself the $70-90 and just head down to the humane society where they will actually vet your pet and provide you with medicine if they are sick.
reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Andrea, we are sorry to hear about Chex Mix. Your partner didn't reach out to our rescue until a week after adoption. At that time, the rescue director gave him feedback based on symptoms he was describing. They heard nothing back regarding the situation after the initial email. The $140 fee is due to the complete vetting, including additional testing that many other places do not complete. Mac Tabby does not take any portion of this fee - the entire amount goes back to the rescue. We are separate entities. Mac Tabby is a separate business who facilitates finding cats homes through the partnership with our rescue so that fee goes back to saving more cats. And yes, we DO know the cat's current conditions. Our team at Mac Tabby is with them 12 hours per day and we assess them on charts twice daily. You noted that his eyes were watery a day after adoption. This is very possible since the stress of adoption, traveling and a new home lowers younger cat's immune systems. It is not uncommon. If the symptoms started the next day, then it's possible he had no symptoms while with us before adoption. We have had almost 1,000 adoptions with our current rescue partner and we know they work with those who need help. Perhaps the lack of communication after the initial email sent back added to the frustration on your behalf, but they had no way of knowing if there were still issues. There is also an option to return a cat within two weeks with a refund if you're unable to keep them for any reason. We are not saying your partner should have relinquished his cat, but we want to be clear to anyone reading this that they don't get "stuck" with a cat with no options. We are compassionate about our cats and feel terrible that Chex Mix doesn't feel well... he's an amazing kitty and we miss him! Please stay in contact with the rescue via email if you need further assist and help.

Hello Adriana! We would like to touch on a few points regarding your review.
Unfortunately, you were 40 minutes late to your booking which started at noon. We held your spot for you for the hour since you did in fact book it online and called to say you were still coming. You booked from 12-1pm. You arrived at 12:40. We greeted you at the register and asked if you'd like to take anything in with you (referring to the menu). We ask all guests the same 5 questions at the register as they enter - and we love for everyone to enjoy a beverage while visiting! Once in the cat room, we showed your son the cats and helped him with the toys while another employee took photos of you and your friend on your phone. Our staff members always stay in the cat room with guests. Our job is to be sure the cats are healthy and happy and guests are attended to. We are sorry to hear that you felt you were being "watched". We also did not ask you to leave for any other reason other than the hour booking was over. Those who booked from 12 - 1 must leave at 1pm so we can allow the 1pm guests who booked into the space. We were fully booked at the 1pm and 2pm hour - so there would be no way to extend your visit. We allow 12 people at a time to visit the cats, which is why we require reservations. In the booking process - it states, "Please plan additional time for parking / check-in / beverage orders. All reservations start promptly at the time chosen in your booking. You may reschedule by calling 24 hours in advance. There are no refunds for no-shows or cancelations". We are very dedicated to our customer service and our team does everything we can to treat everyone who visits us with fairness and respect. We wanted to be sure you knew that we do appreciate your business and coming to visit - we believe the misunderstanding came from your shorter visit due to your late arrival. If you visit again while in Charlotte - please plan to come a few minutes earlier then your time booked to be sure there is time to place a beverage order if you so choose, check in, and get the FULL hour with the cats and all the goodness they have to offer!

Hello all! If there has ever been a hard review for me to write, it is this one. I have been debating it for days, but I decided it’s a big enough issue that I should follow through with it. I’d like to preface by saying that me and my boyfriend have come to the Charlotte Mac Tabby location for 3+ years. We have been loyal customers. It’s a date we always look forward to and count the days down on!

Last Wednesday I had a laparoscopic ovarian cystectomy with the addition of a surprise laparoscopic uterosacral nerve ablation. I decided to book a one-hour kitty date for me and my boyfriend, who goes to college in Virginia and came to visit me during this difficult time of my life, for that Saturday to get me out of the house. Oh boy! I woke up that morning feeling the worst I had since the surgery, it was rough but I decided the date would be worth it. Or so I thought.

For those used to the Charlotte location, you know there is a troublesome flight of stairs leading up to the door. About 20-30. I had told my boyfriend to stay behind me in case I fall or become weak, as this was the first time I had been out of the house since surgery as well as the first flight of stairs I walked up. For some reason, a worker of Mac Tabby (white, middle-aged+, average height male) who was sweeping the area above the stairs decided it would be the perfect time to make side comments about how “it must be such a workout going up those stairs” for me. We did not respond at first, as I was more concerned with not tripping over my own feet, however; he did not let this stop him. He continued making the same comment 2 or 3 more times about the stairs being “such a workout” for me. Once I got to the top of the stairs I informed him I had surgery, but rather than apologize he doubled down and said once more how rough it must be to walk up some stairs with a sarcastic tone. Wow, how kind.

I tried to not let it bother me at first, although later I lost that battle and brought it up to a worker who seemed to understand where I was coming from and decided to get the owner involved. Once the owner came over she did not seem as understanding. At all. Right off the bat, how I felt was dismissed by her and she made excuses for him saying they say that to each other all the time and there’s no way he could’ve known I had surgery. That’s the point! You are coworkers, you know each other. He does NOT KNOW ME! Or what I’ve been through!! I am highly disappointed that it took me showing this lady my stitches and bruises for her to act as if she knew where I was coming from. Bottom line, don’t make comments about your customers you do with your coworkers. Do not make comments with them, especially ones that can be taken as very rude and demeaning. You do not know what people struggle with every day. Some people have disabilities, and climbing those stairs may be the hardest part of their day- don’t be a jackass about it! Don’t make it harder! I don’t care if you make comments to each other at work, be careful who you say that shit to because I am not your coworker I am a paying customer who crawled out of her bed after a very rough surgery to try to have a better day. This experience demonstrates a lack of management understanding. Which is upsetting since me and my boyfriend really loved the experience this place brought us.

Needless to say, me and my boyfriend will not be back to this location. We will try our luck at other locations and pray we don’t have workers make comments about our body there. This has been a disappointing experience, to say the least.

Their drinks are pretty good though and the cats are innocent in all this. Adopt them!!
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Hey Allie! I was the one who spoke with you at the cafe that day. I was surprised to read this review, as I thought we left our conversation in a good place. We DO appreciate you, we LOVE our customers, we apologized that you felt personally attacked by that comment, but it truly was not directed AT you. I was simply trying to convey that, and mentioned that he had NO idea of your surgery, at which point you showed me your stomach scars.
I was not dismissing you. I heard you and felt terrible that you felt that way about the comment. Our employee said he was just trying to make conversation, and felt bad it came across as rude. The stairs ARE a workout (22!) and sometimes the "phew! This is a workout!" comment is made in jest as conversations between us and our customers. Either the customer mentioning it TO us, or vice versa. It was not meant to be demeaning in any way, which is what I had tried to explain. We were saddened to hear you felt that way. I'm sorry that I did not seem genuine to you during our discussion. People matter to me. You matter to me! I know you have been a customer for a long time and I wanted you to enjoy your experience. We hope you are healing well, and if you choose not to visit Charlotte again - our other locations aren't far and we know the kitties would love to see you! Take care...

reviews_data.owner_answer: Hello Ginger! Our cats are flea treated prior to arrival and come from a flea free facility. We have never had an issue with fleas let alone have ever even seen one in Mac Tabby. We are inspected by the state Agriculture Dept and have strict codes to abide by. It is possible this flea came in with you from elsewhere if you saw one on your person. As far as sleepy cats, we don't require them to perform. They are animals on cycles. Our website states the best time to visit with them given what you'd like to get out of your visit. Some people prefer to sit near a cuddled sleepy kitty and don't mind them being that way. Other people who prefer to play typically come at 11 or noon when we open. Or later in the evening when they are naturally more active. Again, it is individual. For the most part, with 12 cats in the lounge, there are always a few to engage with at any time. Picking up a toy or throwing their toys and interacting makes them more interested in engaging -- otherwise cats will be cats! They make you work for it ;) Any cat who doesn't want to be bothered by people have the opportunity to escape into their back room to rest. So we assure you that if they are out on the floor, they don't mind being pet and loved even though they are resting. We hope you come again during an hour that suits more of an experience that you were hoping for. Thanks for stopping in!

reviews_data.review_text: My  partner adopted a kitten from this place and the kitten essentially came to his home with a cold (Chex Mix). My partner was told that any watering eyes or sneezing is normal for kittens as they adjust, but within days this developed into a cold. His kitten now has red watery eyes and tons of sneezes.Usually, this is not a problem as most organizations will offer a low cost visit at an affiliated clinic and help the kitten they just adopted. However, after paying $140 for an adoption fee, which is steep and more than I’ve ever paid for my healthy humane society cats, they essentially told him to go find his own vet after a WEEK from his adoption date. Like I said before, the baby’s eyes were watery the DAY AFTER he got the kitten and they did not take the situation seriously. Just be warned that this organization facilitates over priced adoptions under the guise that the cats have been vetted but really they have been given shots, months prior, and they have no idea on the kittens current condition! Save yourself the $70-90 and just head down to the humane society where they will actually vet your pet and provide you with medicine if they are sick.
reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Andrea, we are sorry to hear about Chex Mix. Your partner didn't reach out to our rescue until a week after adoption. At that time, the rescue director gave him feedback based on symptoms he was describing. They heard nothing back regarding the situation after the initial email. The $140 fee is due to the complete vetting, including additional testing that many other places do not complete. Mac Tabby does not take any portion of this fee - the entire amount goes back to the rescue. We are separate entities. Mac Tabby is a separate business who facilitates finding cats homes through the partnership with our rescue so that fee goes back to saving more cats. And yes, we DO know the cat's current conditions. Our team at Mac Tabby is with them 12 hours per day and we assess them on charts twice daily. You noted that his eyes were watery a day after adoption. This is very possible since the stress of adoption, traveling and a new home lowers younger cat's immune systems. It is not uncommon. If the symptoms started the next day, then it's possible he had no symptoms while with us before adoption. We have had almost 1,000 adoptions with our current rescue partner and we know they work with those who need help. Perhaps the lack of communication after the initial email sent back added to the frustration on your behalf, but they had no way of knowing if there were still issues. There is also an option to return a cat within two weeks with a refund if you're unable to keep them for any reason. We are not saying your partner should have relinquished his cat, but we want to be clear to anyone reading this that they don't get "stuck" with a cat with no options. We are compassionate about our cats and feel terrible that Chex Mix doesn't feel well... he's an amazing kitty and we miss him! Please stay in contact with the rescue via email if you need further assist and help.

Hello Adriana! We would like to touch on a few points regarding your review.
Unfortunately, you were 40 minutes late to your booking which started at noon. We held your spot for you for the hour since you did in fact book it online and called to say you were still coming. You booked from 12-1pm. You arrived at 12:40. We greeted you at the register and asked if you'd like to take anything in with you (referring to the menu). We ask all guests the same 5 questions at the register as they enter - and we love for everyone to enjoy a beverage while visiting! Once in the cat room, we showed your son the cats and helped him with the toys while another employee took photos of you and your friend on your phone. Our staff members always stay in the cat room with guests. Our job is to be sure the cats are healthy and happy and guests are attended to. We are sorry to hear that you felt you were being "watched". We also did not ask you to leave for any other reason other than the hour booking was over. Those who booked from 12 - 1 must leave at 1pm so we can allow the 1pm guests who booked into the space. We were fully booked at the 1pm and 2pm hour - so there would be no way to extend your visit. We allow 12 people at a time to visit the cats, which is why we require reservations. In the booking process - it states, "Please plan additional time for parking / check-in / beverage orders. All reservations start promptly at the time chosen in your booking. You may reschedule by calling 24 hours in advance. There are no refunds for no-shows or cancelations". We are very dedicated to our customer service and our team does everything we can to treat everyone who visits us with fairness and respect. We wanted to be sure you knew that we do appreciate your business and coming to visit - we believe the misunderstanding came from your shorter visit due to your late arrival. If you visit again while in Charlotte - please plan to come a few minutes earlier then your time booked to be sure there is time to place a beverage order if you so choose, check in, and get the FULL hour with the cats and all the goodness they have to offer!

The cat room is large enough that even though there were 10 people in there, it didn't seem crowded at all. We were free to move around and visit with several of the kittens; some were sleeping, some were active and playful. I was pretty excited that we could bring toys for them as well - as soon as we got there one of them practically jumped into my bag to get the catnip mice out :) Though we didn't get anything at the cafe', I like that there was a pretty big assortment and that you could bring your selection into the cat room with you (or they'd bring it in to you if you were already there). Knowing that a small fee goes to help so many of these wonderful cats, I'd be visiting there weekly if I lived in the area. I will absolutely make another stop in the next time I'm in the area.

Loved this place- I didn't do the full five stars only because it was my first time being here and there were a lot of unsupervised kids present. Regardless awesome and friendly staff and great selection of drinks and cute kitties!
